knn - k nearest neighbours

Clustering is an unsupevised machine learning technique. We can use it when we want to look at groups, but we have no means of labelling them.

There are a number of character variables that would be better as factors, so we can use them more effectively. Lets swap them over.

One way to do this is use the as.factor() function.

Some of these like age and income are actually ordered, so we will tell R what the order should be. To do that, we use the factor() function and the levels argument.

loan_book$BorrowerAge <- factor(loan_book$BorrowerAge, levels = c("<20", "20-29", "30-39" , "40-49", "50-59", "60-69", "70-79", "80-89"))
str(loan_book$BorrowerAge)
##  Factor w/ 8 levels "<20","20-29",..: 6 2 4 3 4 3 5 4 4 4 ...

Lets go ahead and do the rest.

loan_book$FinancePurpose <- as.factor(loan_book$FinancePurpose)
loan_book$EmploymentStatus <- as.factor(loan_book$EmploymentStatus)
loan_book$BorrowerIncome <- factor(loan_book$BorrowerIncome, levels = c("<$50K", "$50-100K", "$100-150K", ">$150K"))
loan_book$HousingStatus <- as.factor(loan_book$HousingStatus)
loan_book$Gender <- as.factor(loan_book$Gender)
loan_book$EarlyPaymentsMade <- as.factor(loan_book$EarlyPaymentsMade)
loan_book$RepaymentStatus <- as.factor(loan_book$RepaymentStatus)

Lets start with a simple line chart for the contract date (the date the loan was signed off) and the rate of interest paid by the borrower.

ggplot(loan_book) +
  geom_line(aes(ContractDate, AnnualRate), 
            colour = "steelblue4") +
  theme_light()+
  xlab("Date of contract") +
  ylab("Annual rate paid by borrower")

In technical terms, we like to refer to a chart like this as a hot mess. For the love of all thats geeky, never let a chart like this off your hard drive. Im only including this here so you know what to do if you find one of these: you ask more questions.

Whats going on here? Well its hard to say. The rate being paid each year is largely between around 3% and 10% with some variation outside that. This is where we start using what consultants call business acumen and normal people call common sense.

Whats something that could be causing a big variation in the rate paid between two loans contracted within a very short period? Interest rates are pretty stable for retail loans, right? Well, heres where domain knowledge is useful. If you know anything about finance, you know the loan term is a good candidate to start with. Lets see what we can dig up there.

If we want to see what the relationship between the loan term and annual rate paid is, a scatterplot is a good first step.

ggplot(loan_book) +
  geom_point(aes(LoanTerm, AnnualRate), 
            colour = "steelblue4") +
  theme_light()+
  xlab("Loan Term") +
  ylab("Annual rate paid by borrower")

Well, no easy answers here. While it does look like there is a relationship between annual rate and loan term, where annual rate increases with loan term - there are a few observations with very long loan terms that dont fit the pattern at all.

Welcome to real data.

The best option is simply to keep digging here, in my opinion.

What about financed amount and the annual rate?

ggplot(loan_book) +
  geom_point(aes(FinanceAmount, AnnualRate), 
            colour = "steelblue4") +
  theme_light()+
  xlab("Financed Amount") +
  ylab("Annual rate paid by borrower")

Again, no easy answers! Why on earth would people borrowing the same or similar amounts be paying such remarkably different interest rates? What are the factors that could be in play here? Heres that domain knowledge coming through again- it could be something about the person (are they risky?) or the loan (is the loan more risky?).

What makes a person risky? Their income, their borrowing history (not given), their employment and even their age can be perceived as risk.

What about a loan? The financed amount, the status of the loan (is it in arrears), the term - all these things can contribute to risk too.

That said, we have discovered something interesting - the financed amount for Ratesetter customers is truncated at zero. This makes sense: nobody is borrowing negative amounts. Most of the data is clustered under $10 000, but there are two distinct groups - those with a higher rate, and those with a lower for the same amount financed. What could be the reason for this behaviour?

Lets see if we can colour off the difference in loan term in this chart by creating a variable called shortTerm. This variable is 1 if the loan has a term of 24 months or less and zero otherwise. For convenience when plotting, well turn it into a factor variable with labels and add it to the loan book.

shortTerm <- ifelse(loan_book$LoanTerm <= 24, 1, 0)
shortTerm <- factor(shortTerm)
levels(shortTerm) <- c("> 24 months", "<= 24 months")
loan_book <- cbind(loan_book, shortTerm)

ggplot(loan_book) +
  geom_point(aes(FinanceAmount, AnnualRate, colour = shortTerm)) +
  theme_light()+
  xlab("Financed Amount") +
  ylab("Annual rate paid by borrower")

And bingo! We now have a pretty good idea of whats causing the difference in interest rates: its the loan term. Short term loans are less risky than long term ones and the borrower is compensated with a lower interest rate.

Actually doing the machine learning

First we need to standardise the numeric variables. Well write a function to do this:

standardise_variables <- function(our_variable){
  z_score <- (our_variable - mean(our_variable))/sd(our_variable)
  return(z_score)
}

Now we have define our function, we can apply it to our data frame, but lets call it by a new name so we know whats going on. Were going to use the package purrr, so if you dont have it installed, youll need to use install.packages("purrr").

The useful thing about purrr is that you can apply a function to many columns of a data frame.

library(purrr)
df_numeric <- loan_book[,3:6]
ml_df <- map_dfr(df_numeric, standardise_variables)

# Let's add repayment status

ml_df$RepaymentStatus <- loan_book$RepaymentStatus

OK, so we need to define our training and test sets. We should always do this randomly, so heres one way of doing it. Ill show you another later. Well take 70% for training and 30% for test.

p = 0.7 # 70% of the set
n_rows <- round(nrow(ml_df)*0.7, digits = 0) # number of rows that would be
randomIndex <- runif(n_rows, min = 1, max = nrow(ml_df))

train_set <- ml_df[randomIndex,]
test_set <- ml_df[-randomIndex,]

Lets use the class package to run knn algorithm. Lets see how it goes on the repayment status label we added earlier.

#install.packages("class")
library(class)
train_labels <- train_set[[5]]
test_labels <- test_set[[5]]
predictions <- knn(train = train_set[,1:4], test = test_set[,1:4], cl = train_labels, k = 3)

Lets see how good we did!

#install.packages("gmodels")
library(gmodels)
